Yemeni medical malpractices laws in the absence of clear contraceptive laws lead to women facing stigma and condemnation during unsafe abortions, with even mortality rates following unsafe abortion in the range higher than India and Pakistan. Attitudes towards abortion are defined by social networks, belonging to politicaland religious organisations, and/or community. Religious interpretation plays a small role in shaping women’s attitudes in Yemen.

Zambia

Generally, cultural and religious sanction is expressed in the customary and statutory laws against abortion. However, in practice, Chilombo in 1971 observed that sex outside marriage or that leading to unwanted pregnancies were exceptions to the laws of the land.

Most men interviewed by Chilombo in 1971 “…supported the inclusion of provision for the legal termination of pregnancy on the grounds of fetal deformity or mental handicap, on the ground of illegitimacy of the child and on the grounds of the mother’s own physical health or mental health”. Abortion is a sensitive issue in society which needs to be tackled with caution. Although there are efforts towards legalizing abortion, many times the project is not successful.

Separately, Northern Ireland remains outside the jurisdiction of the Republic of Ireland, and must adhere to its own abortion laws based on the 1945 Offences Against the Person Act.

Barretto’s research appeal is useful and gives a particular grouping of countries, which need to be specifically pursued.
